Why This Is Asked: This question tests plan-based thinking for multi-tenant, latency-sensitive workloads. It combines CPU, memory, and I/O isolation with NUMA awareness and observability, requiring concrete trade-offs and a rollout strategy.

Key Concepts:
- cgroup v2 namespaces and per-tenant resource hierarchies
- CPU and memory isolation with NUMA binding
- I/O scheduling: mq-deadline for low-latency, bfq for fairness with per-tenant quotas
- Memory policies: mbind for NUMA-local allocation, mlcked memory with memlock
- Observability: eBPF-based latency tracing, perf for CPU profiling, iostat for I/O metrics
- Safe rollout strategy: canary deployment with automated rollback triggers

Code Example (eBPF for per-tenant latency measurement):
```c
#include <linux/bpf.h>
#include <bpf/bpf_helpers.h>

struct { __uint(type, BPF_MAP_TYPE_HASH); 
          __type(key, __u32); 
          __type(value, __u64); } latency_map SEC(".maps");

SEC("tracepoint/sched/sched_wakeup")
int measure_latency(void *ctx) {
    __u64 ts = bpf_ktime_get_ns();
    __u32 pid = bpf_get_current_pid_tgid();
    bpf_map_update_elem(&latency_map, &pid, &ts, BPF_ANY);
    return 0;
}
```

